Objective¶

Use Supervised Learning to build a model that can predict house prices in the US given its details

Background Info¶

In the US, there are many types of houses for various prices. Usually houses that are better furnished or bigger are priced higher. But their location might matter too.

The Dataset¶

Variable Meaning
House ID Unique house identifier ranging from 0 to 544
City Which city the house is located
House Area Size of the house in square meters
No. of Bedrooms How many bedrooms in the house
No. of Toilets How many toilets in the house
Stories The number of stories in the house
Renovation Status How well the house is renovated
Price The price of the house in US dollars

Total Rows: 545

Features: 7

Target: Price

Features: Remaining Columns

Feature Engineering¶

there is no imbalance in the data. So no need complex preprocessing. I will just go to splitting data and creating the pipeline. I will do ordinal and one hot encoding here because might have problems in cross validation if data set is small and some categories are not seem by the model

In [4]:
X = df.iloc[:,1:-1]
y = (df["Price ($)"]/1000)# change units
enc = OrdinalEncoder(categories=[['unfurnished', 'semi-furnished', 'furnished']])
X["Renovation Status"]= enc.fit_transform(X["Renovation Status"].values.reshape(-1,1))
X["Renovation Status"] = X["Renovation Status"].astype(int)
# dont want decimal cuz smote might create data like 1.5\
X = pd.get_dummies(X,columns=["City"])

X_train,X_test,y_train,y_test = train_test_split(X,y,train_size=0.80,random_state=99)
features = X_train.columns

Creating Pipeline¶

Need reuse later

In [5]:
from sklearn import set_config
def Pipe(name,model):
  set_config(transform_output="pandas")
  pipe = Pipeline([
      ("preprocessing", 
          ColumnTransformer([ 
                          ("num",FunctionTransformer(lambda x: np.log(x.astype(int)+1)),[0,1,2,3]),
                          ("scale",StandardScaler(),[0,1,2,3])
                          ])),
          (name,model)
    ])
  return pipe

Scoring¶

  • MAE = $\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n|x_i-x|$ Basically the absolute difference between the predicted and actual values, averaged
  • R2: 1 - (sum of squared residuals)/(total sum of squares) Basically tells you how well the model predicts a outcome.
  • MAPE: Similiar to MAE but percentage instead

I will be using r2 primarily as it ranges from 0 to 1 where negative values mean the model predicts worse than a constant function that predicts mean.

In this project I will focus on maximising r^2 as it is easier to interpret

In [61]:
results = []
for name, model in models:
    pipe = Pipe(name, model)
    pipe.fit(X_train,y_train)
    score = cross_validate(pipe, X_train, y_train, cv=5, scoring={
        'mae': "neg_mean_absolute_error",
        'r2': 'r2',
        'mape': 'neg_mean_absolute_percentage_error'
    })
    needed = {
        "name": name,
        "mse": np.mean(score["test_mae"])*-1,
        "r2": np.mean(score["test_r2"]),
        "mape": np.mean(score["test_mape"]*-1)
    }
    results.append(needed)

Compare Learning Curve¶

In [24]:
test_models = [("DummyRegressor",DummyRegressor()),("RandomForest", RandomForestRegressor()),
        ("GradientBoosting", GradientBoostingRegressor()),("Ridge",Ridge()),
         ("Lasso",Lasso()),("Elasticnet",ElasticNet())]
fig,ax=plt.subplots(2,3,figsize=(20,10),sharey=True)
score_df = []
for i, (name,model) in enumerate(test_models):
  pipe = Pipe(name,model)
  pipe.fit(X_train,y_train)
  sizes, training_scores, testing_scores = learning_curve(estimator= pipe, X=X_train, y= y_train, cv=5, scoring='r2', train_sizes=np.linspace(0.01, 1.0, 50))
  testing_scores[testing_scores<0] =0 # set neg values to 0
  score_df = pd.DataFrame({"size":(sizes),"train":np.mean(training_scores,axis=1),"test":np.mean(testing_scores,axis=1)})
  row = i//3
  col = i%3
  ax[row,col].plot(score_df["size"],score_df["train"],label = "train")
  ax[row,col].plot(score_df["size"],score_df["test"],label="test")
  ax[row,col].set_title(name)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

testing = [
 ("Ridge", Ridge(max_iter=10000)),
  ("Lasso",Lasso(max_iter=100000)),
  ("ElasticNet", ElasticNet(max_iter=10000))]
params = [
    {
        'Ridge__alpha': [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 0.5, 1.0, 10.0, 100.0],
        'Ridge__fit_intercept': [True, False],
        'Ridge__solver': ['auto', 'svd', 'cholesky', 'lsqr', 'sparse_cg', 'sag', 'saga']
    },
    {
        'Lasso__alpha': [0.001,0.01, 0.1, 0.5, 1.0, 10.0, 100.0],
        'Lasso__fit_intercept': [True, False],
        'Lasso__selection': ['cyclic', 'random']
    },
    {
        'ElasticNet__alpha':[0.001,0.01, 0.1, 0.5, 1.0, 10.0, 100.0],
        'ElasticNet__l1_ratio':np.arange(0.1,1,0.1)
    }
]
best_models = []
for i, (name,model) in enumerate(testing):
  pipe = Pipe(name,model)
  rand_search = RandomizedSearchCV(pipe,params[i] , cv=5, return_train_score=False,scoring="r2")
  rand_search.fit(X_train, y_train)
  best_models.append(rand_search.best_estimator_)
  print(name,"\n",rand_search.best_params_,"\n", rand_search.best_score_)
